      "writtenOn": "2015-07-15T08:27:00Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Generally speaking, try to quote directory paths in case they contain spaces (something a lot more likely on Windows than Linux or OSX).\n\nAlso, so just you know, posix _direct_ assignments don\u0027t need quoting, i.e. a line like:\n\n   X\u003d$Y\n\nwill always work as expected, even if $Y contains spaces. The issue comes only when expanding $Y as non-assigment expression parameters (writing portable shell scripts is hard). And since we\u0027re talking about that:\n\n  local X\u003d$Y\n\nwill not always work as expected if $Y contains spaces, depending on your shell implementation (some of them treat \u0027local\u0027 as a builtin keyword, and then the expression above is seen as a direct assignment; some others treat \u0027local\u0027 as a special function call, huuu), so this line is\nbetter rewritten as:\n\n  local X\u003d\"$Y\"\n\nor:\n\n   local X\n    X\u003d$Y",
      "revId": "eb2a6b186d13f085e16c771d8c1919978b8fc58e",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889",
      "unresolved": false
